🔄 <i>Switching to Care Mode for precise analysis...</i>

<blockquote>🟠 <b>CARE MODE</b>

Hi Emma, I&#x27;m glad that summary was helpful for your notes! It&#x27;s excellent that you&#x27;re calling the vet first thing.

When you call, you can tell them exactly what you told me:

*   &quot;My 7-month-old Golden Retriever, Buddy, started limping on his back right leg yesterday after a long walk at the park. It was intermittent then.&quot;
*   &quot;This morning, the limping is significantly worse; he&#x27;s barely putting any weight on that back leg.&quot;
*   &quot;I&#x27;ve also noticed visible puffiness around his right knee area compared to his left leg.&quot;
*   &quot;He&#x27;s still eating, drinking, and seems otherwise bright (tail wags), but the physical symptoms are very concerning.&quot;

This information clearly communicates the worsening condition and new physical signs, which will help the vet understand the urgency.

**Regarding pain medication:** **Please do not give Buddy any human pain medications like ibuprofen or Tylenol (acetaminophen).** These medications are formulated for humans and can be very dangerous, even toxic, to dogs. They can cause severe side effects such as stomach ulcers, kidney failure, and liver damage, even in small doses. Your vet will be able to assess Buddy properly and prescribe safe, appropriate pain relief specifically for dogs if needed.

The best thing to do for Buddy right now is to keep him comfortable and still until you can get him to the vet.</blockquote>
